{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048180,"nonce":"iUiDk5qH0GhiF+siuCp2/Huj76Q=","title":"Feature: DAE/Acausal subgraphs with domain-specific component palettes","message":"[Imported from GitHub #49] (created 2026-01-30T17:27:01Z)\n\n## Summary\n\nAdd support for **DAE (Differential-Algebraic Equation) subgraphs** that use implicit equation solving internally, with domain-specific acausal components. This would enable modeling systems with algebraic constraints (e.g., musculoskeletal dynamics, electrical circuits) while maintaining our existing causal graph architecture at the outer level.\n\n## Concept\n\n### Subgraph as Solver Scope\n\nA subgraph could declare \"I use DAE/acausal solving internally\":\n- **Inside** the subgraph: acausal components with bidirectional ports (Spring, Damper, Mass, etc.)\n- **Outside** the subgraph: normal causal interface (state in → state out)\n- The DAE solver resolves constraint equations internally; from outside it looks like any other component\n\n### Domain-Specific Component Palettes\n\nWhen editing inside a DAE subgraph, the component palette would show acausal components organized by physical domain:\n\n**Mechanical (Translational):**\n- Mass, Spring, Damper, Force Source, Position/Velocity Sensors\n\n**Mechanical (Rotational):**\n- Inertia, Torsional Spring, Rotational Damper, Gear Ratio, Torque Source\n\n**Electrical:**\n- Resistor, Capacitor, Inductor, Voltage/Current Sources, Ground\n\n**Thermal:**\n- Thermal Mass, Thermal Resistor, Heat Source\n\n### Wiring Semantics\n\nInside DAE subgraphs:\n- Wires are **bidirectional** (no input/output distinction)\n- Ports represent physical connection points, not data flow\n- Multiple wires can connect to a single port (conservation laws apply)\n\n### Example Use Case\n\n```\n[Task] → [Controller (normal subgraph)] → [Musculoskeletal (DAE subgraph)]\n                                                     ↓\n                                           Inside: muscles, tendons, bones\n                                           with stiffness/damping constraints\n                                           solved via implicit DAE methods\n```\n\n## Implementation Considerations\n\n1. **Solver integration**: Would likely use `diffrax` with implicit methods, or a dedicated DAE solver\n2. **Subgraph metadata**: Need to store solver type (explicit vs DAE) in graph spec\n3. **Boundary compilation**: Acausal internals must be \"compiled\" to causal interface at subgraph boundary\n4. **UI changes**: Component palette, wire rendering, and port behavior change based on subgraph type\n\n## Prior Art\n\nThis pattern is well-established in simulation tools:\n- Modelica and tools like OpenModelica, Dymola\n- MATLAB/Simulink with Simscape\n- Collimator.ai's acausal blocks\n- 20-sim\n\nThe key insight from these tools is that acausal modeling is most useful when scoped to physical subsystems, while the outer control/signal flow remains causal.\n\n## Why This Matters for Feedbax\n\nNeuroscience applications often involve:\n- Muscle-tendon dynamics with stiff springs and kinematic constraints\n- Multi-body dynamics (arm segments, joints) with algebraic position constraints\n- Potentially neural mass models with fast/slow dynamics requiring implicit solving\n\nCurrently we approximate these with explicit Euler stepping, but true DAE support would enable more accurate and stable simulation of stiff systems.\n\n---\n\n*Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e*","files":null}]}